  "prompt": "How do I create Drupal modules?",
  "response": "Creating Drupal modules can be a rewarding experience, allowing you to customize and extend the functionality of your Drupal website. Here's a breakdown of the process, covering the essential steps and concepts:\n\n**1. Understand the Basics**\n\n*   **What is a Module?** A module is a collection of PHP, CSS, JavaScript, and other files that add specific functionality to Drupal.  It's like an extension or plugin.\n*   **Why create a module?**\n    *   **Custom Functionality:**  Implement features unique to your website.\n    *   **Reusability:** Package functionality for use on multiple Drupal sites.\n    *   **Organization:**  Keep your custom code separate from Drupal core.\n    *   **Contribution:**  Share your module with the Drupal community.\n\n**2. Set Up Your Development Environment**\n\n*   **Local Drupal Installation:**  Develop and test modules on a local environment (using tools like XAMPP, MAMP, Docker, Lando, DDEV, or DrupalVM). This prevents breaking your live website.\n*   **Code Editor/IDE:** Use a code editor that supports PHP, like VS Code, PhpStorm, Sublime Text, or Atom.\n*   **Drush/Drupal Console (Recommended):** These command-line tools significantly speed up development tasks, like creating module scaffolding, clearing caches, and running updates.\n\n**3. Module Structure**\n\nThe core structure of a Drupal module includes:\n\n*   **`[module_name].info.yml`:**  (Required)  Contains metadata about the module, such as its name, description, core compatibility, and dependencies.\n*   **`[module_name].module`:** (Required, but can be empty initially) The main PHP file where you'll define hooks and functions that extend Drupal's functionality.\n\nOptionally, you might have:\n\n*   **`config/` directory:**  Stores configuration files (for example, `install`, `schema`, `optional`).\n*   **`src/` directory:**  Recommended for organizing classes, interfaces, and other PHP code following Drupal's object-oriented approach. Common subdirectories include:\n    *   `Controller/`:  Contains controller classes that handle requests and render pages.\n    *   `Form/`: Contains form classes for creating and processing forms.\n    *   `Plugin/`: Contains plugin definitions (e.g., for blocks, fields, etc.).\n    *   `Entity/`: Defines custom entity types.\n*   **`templates/` directory:** Contains Twig templates for rendering output.\n*   **`css/`, `js/` directories:**  For CSS and JavaScript files.\n*   **`translations/` directory:** For localization files.\n\n**4. Creating the `.info.yml` File**\n\nThis file is crucial; Drupal uses it to recognize and enable your module.\n\n```yaml\nname: My Custom Module  # Human-readable name\ntype: module            # Indicates this is a module\ndescription: 'A module to do awesome things.' # Short description\ncore_version_requirement: ^9 || ^10  # Drupal core versions supported\npackage: Custom          # Category for the module in the module list (optional)\n\n# Dependencies (optional)\ndependencies:\n  - drupal: node\n  - drupal: views\n\n#  Configure any modules that should be uninstalled when this module is uninstalled (optional)\n# uninstalls:\n#  - other_module\n```\n\n*   **`name`:**  The display name of your module.\n*   **`type`:**  Always `module` for a module.\n*   **`description`:**  A brief explanation of the module's purpose.\n*   **`core_version_requirement`:**  Specifies the Drupal core versions this module is compatible with.  Use `^9` for Drupal 9 and later minor versions, or `^10` for Drupal 10 and later. Using `^9 || ^10` means that the module works with Drupal 9 or Drupal 10.\n*   **`package`:**  Organizes your module within the module administration list (e.g., `Custom`, `Features`).\n*   **`dependencies`:** A list of other Drupal modules that *must* be enabled for your module to function correctly.  Use the module's machine name (e.g., `drupal: node`, `drupal: views`).\n*   **`uninstalls`:** This is an *optional* section. It lists other modules that *must* be uninstalled for your module to be uninstalled correctly. This is useful if your module replaces functionality of another module.\n\n**Example Folder Structure:**\n\n```\nmodules/\n  |-- custom/       # Or 'contrib' for contributed modules\n  |   |-- my_custom_module/\n  |   |   |-- my_custom_module.info.yml\n  |   |   |-- my_custom_module.module\n  |   |   |-- src/\n  |   |   |   |-- Controller/\n  |   |   |   |   |-- MyController.php\n  |   |   |   |-- Form/\n  |   |   |   |   |-- MyForm.php\n  |   |   |   |-- ...\n  |   |   |-- templates/\n  |   |   |   |-- my_template.html.twig\n  |   |   |-- css/\n  |   |   |   |-- my_custom_module.css\n  |   |   |-- js/\n  |   |   |   |-- my_custom_module.js\n```\n\n**5. The `.module` File (Entry Point)**\n\nThis is where the main logic of your module resides. You use *hooks* to interact with Drupal core and other modules.\n\n*   **Hooks:**  Functions with specific names (e.g., `hook_node_insert()`, `hook_form_alter()`, `hook_entity_presave()`) that Drupal calls at certain points in its execution.  You implement these hooks in your `.module` file to modify or react to Drupal's behavior.\n*   **Naming Convention:** Replace `hook` with your module's *machine name* (the name of your module's directory).  For example, if your module is named `my_custom_module`, the hook `hook_node_insert()` would become `my_custom_module_node_insert()`.\n\n**Example `.module` file (`my_custom_module.module`):**\n\n```php\n<?php\n\n/**\n * Implements hook_node_insert().\n *\n * This hook is executed when a new node is created.\n */\nfunction my_custom_module_node_insert(\\Drupal\\Core\\Entity\\EntityInterface $node) {\n  // Get the node type (content type).\n  $node_type = $node->getType();\n\n  // Only act on articles.\n  if ($node_type == 'article') {\n    // Get the current user.\n    $current_user = \\Drupal::currentUser();\n\n    // Log a message.\n    \\Drupal::logger('my_custom_module')->notice('New article created by user @user.', ['@user' => $current_user->getAccountName()]);\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Implements hook_form_alter().\n *\n * Allows altering of existing forms.\n */\nfunction my_custom_module_form_alter(&$form, \\Drupal\\Core\\Form\\FormStateInterface $form_state, $form_id) {\n  // Add a custom submit handler to the node edit form.\n  if ($form_id == 'node_article_edit_form' || $form_id == 'node_article_form') {\n    $form['actions']['submit']['#submit'][] = 'my_custom_module_article_form_submit';\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Custom submit handler for the article form.\n */\nfunction my_custom_module_article_form_submit(&$form, \\Drupal\\Core\\Form\\FormStateInterface $form_state) {\n  $node = $form_state->getFormObject()->getEntity();\n  \\Drupal::messenger()->addMessage('Article saved successfully!');\n  \\Drupal::logger('my_custom_module')->notice('Article saved.');\n}\n```\n\n**Explanation of the example:**\n\n*   **`my_custom_module_node_insert()`:**  This hook runs when a node is created.  It checks if the node is an \"article\" and logs a message with the username of the user who created it.  `\\Drupal::logger()` provides a standard way to log events in Drupal.\n*   **`my_custom_module_form_alter()`:**  This hook lets you modify existing forms.  It adds a custom submit handler function (`my_custom_module_article_form_submit`) to the article node edit and add forms.\n*   **`my_custom_module_article_form_submit()`:**  This is the custom submit handler.  It displays a message to the user and logs the event. `\\Drupal::messenger()` is used to display messages to the user on the page.\n\n**6. Enable Your Module**\n\n1.  **Clear Cache:**  After creating your module files, clear Drupal's cache.  You can do this through the Drupal admin interface (Configuration -> Development -> Performance -> Clear all caches) or using Drush: `drush cr` or Drupal console: `drupal cache:rebuild`.\n2.  **Install/Enable:**  Navigate to the \"Extend\" page in the Drupal admin interface (`/admin/modules` in your browser). Find your module in the list (it will be in the category you specified in the `.info.yml` file). Check the box next to your module and click \"Install.\"  Alternatively, use Drush: `drush en my_custom_module` or Drupal console: `drupal module:install my_custom_module`.\n\n**7.  Key Concepts and Best Practices**\n\n*   **Machine Name:**  Use underscores instead of spaces in your module's machine name (directory name).\n*   **Coding Standards:** Follow Drupal's coding standards (PSR-2 and Drupal-specific rules).  Tools like PHP Code Sniffer (phpcs) and PHP Mess Detector (phpmd) can help you enforce these standards.\n*   **Security:**  Be aware of security vulnerabilities (e.g., SQL injection, cross-site scripting).  Use Drupal's API and functions to properly sanitize and validate user input.\n*   **Configuration:** Use Drupal's configuration management system for storing settings that can be adjusted through the admin interface.  This allows for easy deployment and management of your module's settings.\n*   **Testing:** Write automated tests (using PHPUnit) to ensure your module works correctly and prevent regressions.\n*   **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP):** Embrace Drupal's OOP structure.  Use classes, interfaces, and dependency injection to create maintainable and testable code.  Place these in the `/src` directory.\n*   **Twig Templating:** Use Twig templates for rendering output. This separates presentation logic from your PHP code.  Place templates in the `/templates` directory.\n*   **Hooks:**  Understand the available hooks and choose the appropriate ones for your needs.  See Drupal's API documentation for a complete list of hooks.  Use `hook_help()` to provide helpful information to users on your module's configuration page.\n*   **Namespacing:** Use namespaces for your classes (e.g., `namespace Drupal\\my_custom_module\\Controller;`).\n*   **Dependency Injection:** Use dependency injection to pass services and other dependencies to your classes and functions. This makes your code more testable and flexible.\n*   **Caching:** Use Drupal's caching mechanisms to improve performance.  Cache data that is frequently accessed and rarely changes.\n*   **Documentation:**  Document your code clearly and concisely.  Use comments to explain the purpose of your functions and classes.  Create a README file to describe how to install and use your module.\n\n**8. Advanced Topics**\n\n*   **Creating Custom Entities:**  Define your own data structures with fields, properties, and relationships.\n*   **Developing Blocks:** Create reusable content blocks that can be placed in regions on your website.\n*   **Implementing Plugins:** Extend Drupal's functionality through plugins (e.g., field formatters, views styles, migrate sources).\n*   **Creating Custom Forms:** Build complex forms with custom validation and processing logic.\n*   **Using Services:** Access Drupal's core services and inject them into your classes.\n*   **Writing Automated Tests:**  Use PHPUnit to write unit, functional, and integration tests for your module.\n*   **Config Entities:** Using ConfigEntities to create custom, manageable configuration settings.\n\n**9.  Example: Creating a Simple Block**\n\nLet's create a simple block that displays \"Hello, World!\".\n\n1.  **Create the `[module_name].info.yml` file:**\n\n    ```yaml\n    name: Hello World Block\n    type: module\n    description: A simple module that creates a \"Hello, World!\" block.\n    core_version_requirement: ^9 || ^10\n    package: Custom\n    ```\n\n2.  **Create the `src/Plugin/Block/HelloWorldBlock.php` file:**\n\n    ```php\n    <?php\n\n    namespace Drupal\\hello_world_block\\Plugin\\Block;\n\n    use Drupal\\Core\\Block\\BlockBase;\n\n    /**\n     * Provides a 'Hello World' Block.\n     *\n     * @Block(\n     *   id = \"hello_world_block\",\n     *   admin_label = @Translation(\"Hello World Block\"),\n     *   category = @Translation(\"Custom\")\n     * )\n     */\n    class HelloWorldBlock extends BlockBase {\n\n      /**\n       * {@inheritdoc}\n       */\n      public function build() {\n        return [\n          '#markup' => $this->t('Hello, World!'),\n        ];\n      }\n\n    }\n    ```\n\n3.  **Enable the Module:** Clear the cache and enable the module as described above.\n\n4.  **Place the Block:** Go to the Block Layout page (`/admin/structure/block`) and place the \"Hello World Block\" in a region.\n\n**10. Learning Resources**\n\n*   **Drupal API Documentation:**  [https://api.drupal.org/](https://api.drupal.org/)\n*   **Drupal.org's Module Development Guide:** [https://www.drupal.org/docs/develop/creating-modules](https://www.drupal.org/docs/develop/creating-modules)\n*   **Drupalize.Me:** A subscription-based website with comprehensive Drupal tutorials.\n*   **Drupal Easy:** Another great resource for Drupal learning.\n*   **Stack Overflow (Drupal Tag):** [https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/drupal](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/drupal)\n*   **Drupal Slack:** A real-time chat platform for Drupal developers.\n\nBy following these steps and utilizing the available resources, you can create powerful and customized Drupal modules to enhance your websites. Remember to start with small, manageable tasks and gradually increase the complexity of your modules as you gain experience.  Good luck!\n",
